Variable Effects of C-Terminal Fusions on FLS2 Function: Not All Epitope Tags 
Are Created Equal.

Hurst CH(1)(2), Turnbull D(1), Myles SM(1), Leslie K(1)(2), Keinath NF(3), 
Hemsley PA(4)(2).

Author information:
(1)Division of Plant Sciences, School of Life Sciences, University of Dundee, 
Dundee DD1 5EH, United Kingdom.
(2)Cell and Molecular Sciences, James Hutton Institute, Invergowrie, Dundee DD2 
5DA, United Kingdom.
(3)Department of Plant Developmental Biology, Centre for Organismal Studies, 
Heidelberg University, 69120 Heidelberg, Germany.
(4)Division of Plant Sciences, School of Life Sciences, University of Dundee, 
Dundee DD1 5EH, United Kingdom p.a.hemsley@dundee.ac.uk.

Receptor-like kinases (RLKs) are the largest family of proteins in plants and 
are responsible for perceiving the vast majority of extracellular stimuli. Thus, 
RLKs function in diverse processes, including sensing pathogen attacks, 
regulating symbiotic interactions, transducing hormone and peptide signals, and 
monitoring cell wall status. However, despite their fundamental role in plant 
biology, very few antibodies are available against RLKs, which necessitates the 
use of epitope tags and fluorescent protein fusions in biochemical analyses such 
as immunoblot analysis and intracellular visualization. Epitope tags are widely 
used and are typically assumed to be benign, with no influence on protein 
function. FLAGELLIN SENSITIVE2 (FLS2) is the receptor for bacterial flagellin 
and often is used as a model for RLK function. Previous work implies that 
carboxyl-terminal epitope fusions to FLS2 maintain protein function. Here, a 
detailed complementation analysis of Arabidopsis (Arabidopsis thaliana) fls2 
